<p>In this correct sentence, itâ€™s broken up into two smaller sentences, and there are some new words too.</p>
<p>The word <strong>â€œSokoâ€</strong> gets used which roughly translates to <strong>â€œthereâ€</strong>, and similar to this thereâ€™s the word <strong>â€œKokoâ€</strong> which means <strong>â€œhereâ€</strong> and <strong>â€œAsokoâ€</strong> which means <strong>â€œover thereâ€</strong></p>
<p>Some other words which are used here are <strong>â€œdakaraâ€</strong> - this word is the same as <strong>â€œkaraâ€</strong> with <strong>â€œdaâ€</strong> added on the front, and we add the <strong>â€œdaâ€</strong> if itâ€™s a noun or an adjective in front of it, if itâ€™s a verb in front of it, just <strong>â€œkaraâ€</strong> is used.</p>
<p>If I wanted the previous sentence in one sentence, I could also write:</p>
